PAPER 1 Mathematical Applications (20 questions, 75 mins, no calculator)
Topic frequencies across all years:
Algebra & Functions 30-35% of questions (6,7 questions)
Appears in every single paper. Focus on: polynomial factorisation, factor theorem, remainder theorem, composite/inverse functions, transformations. This is the single biggest topic.
Calculus — 25–30% (5–6 questions)
Also in every paper. Differentiation (chain rule, stationary points, optimisation) and integration (definite integrals, areas, substitution). Huge focus area.
Coordinate Geometry — 15–20% (3–4 questions)
Circles, straight lines, perpendicular/parallel gradients, tangents. Comes up constantly.
Trigonometry — 10–15% (2–3 questions)
Solving trig equations in given ranges, identities, radians/arc length.
Sequences & Series — 10–15% (2–3 questions)
Arithmetic/geometric progressions, sum to infinity.
Probability/Combinatorics — 5–10% (1–2 questions)
Permutations, combinations, conditional probability.

PAPER 2 — Mathematical Reasoning (20 questions, 75 mins)
This is where most people struggle. It tests logic, not just maths. The main patterns:
Proof & Logic — appears in every paper
Identifying valid/invalid arguments, counterexamples, necessary vs sufficient conditions. This is the hardest to prepare for.
True/False statement analysis
Given a statement, determine if it's always/sometimes/never true.
Error spotting
Find the mistake in a given proof or argument.

KEY PATTERNS across all papers:

Polynomial questions appear in ~80% of papers — always practice factor theorem and root analysis
Integration with hidden structures appears in ~70% — expressions that simplify before integrating
Quadratic optimisation appears in ~60% — completing the square, finding max/min
No calculator means mental arithmetic matters hugely — practice times tables up to 20×20, perfect squares, fraction simplification

What to focus on first (priority order):

Algebra & functions
Calculus (differentiation + integration)
Coordinate geometry
Paper 2 logic/proof skills — most neglected but makes a huge difference

Top tip: On Paper 1, always try substituting easy values (x=0, x=1) to eliminate wrong multiple choice answers — often faster than solving directly.